SIMPLE: frigidity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frigidity
<hw>Fri*gid"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>frigiditas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>frigidit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition or quality of being frigid; coldness;
want of warmth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ice is water congealed by the <qex>frigidity</qex> of the air.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Want of ardor, animation, vivacity, etc.; coldness
of affection or of manner; dullness; stiffness and formality; <as>as,
<ex>frigidity</ex> of a reception, of a bow, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Want of heat or vigor; <as>as, the
<ex>frigidity</ex> of old age</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frigidly</ent>⟦br⟧
